<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1690,2036]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,319,1770,1796]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Thinly lamellar habit, similar to a rooster’s crest, covered by rows of small apical digitiform projections bearing a darker colour on their apices. Bluish gray colour 
<emphasis box="[1003,1084,1810,1835]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">in vivo</emphasis>
, turning into a light shade of brown in ethanol.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1690,2036]" box="[198,351,1890,1916]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,343,1890,1916]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Description</emphasis>
:
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1690,2036]" lastBlockId="30.[151,1437,152,338]" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
The sponge is lamellar, somewhat resembling a rooster’s crest. It is 
<quantity box="[1022,1105,1930,1956]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="cm" value="0.3">0.3 cm</quantity>
thick, 
<quantity box="[1191,1252,1930,1956]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="cm" value="7.0">7 cm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity box="[1376,1436,1930,1956]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="cm" value="7.0">7 cm</quantity>
high. The apical portion of the crest has many small apical digitiform projections 
<quantity box="[1113,1193,1970,1996]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="cm" value="0.6">0.6 cm</quantity>
high (more than 
<number box="[1397,1428,1970,1996]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="50.0">50</number>
) distributed in rows. The small apical digitiform projections remain in the preserved specimen and show their apical portion darker than the base, which has the same colour of the rest of the sponge (
<figureCitation box="[1192,1348,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="30.[151,255,1532,1556]" captionTargetBox="[283,1301,412,1479]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[266,1322,397,1506]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 15: A – D. Aplysina cristagallus sp. n. Holotype (MNRJ 3528). A – B. habit after preservation. C. Skeletal architecture. D. Spongin fibres. Scale bars = A – B. 1 cm, C. 500 µm, D. 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178892/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Figs. 
<number box="[1259,1287,152,178]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" value="15.0">15</number>
A–B
</figureCitation>
). In the upper part of the crest the sponge attains 
<quantity box="[634,692,192,218]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" unit="cm" value="1.0">1 cm</quantity>
in thickness. Small oscula appear on the apex and sides, where small projections are observed also bearing fistules on their top. The surface is very coarsely finely conulose. The colour is bluish gray 
<emphasis box="[453,533,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">in vivo</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[549,619,272,298]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="21.[151,255,1780,1804]" captionTargetBox="[333,1250,184,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[323,1264,177,1762]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 9: A. Aplysina insularis (Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti, 1864: 64). B. Aplysina alcicornis sp. n. in situ, Holotype – MNRJ 5473 (Parque Nacional Marinho dos Abrolhos, BA, Brazil). C. Aplysina cristagallus sp. n. in situ, Holotype— MNRJ 3528 (Prado, BA, Brazil). Scale bar = 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178887/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[604,619,272,298]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
C), which turns into a light shade of brown after preservation in ethanol. Consistency is very soft and flexible.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178892/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" targetBox="[283,1301,412,1479]" targetPageId="30">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,1532,1590]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,1532,1556]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">FIGURE 15:</emphasis>
A–D. 
<taxonomicName box="[368,594,1533,1556]" class="Demospongiae" family="Aplysinidae" genus="Aplysina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Verongida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="cristagallus" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[368,594,1533,1556]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Aplysina cristagallus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[601,652,1533,1556]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
Holotype (MNRJ 3528). A–B. habit after preservation. C. Skeletal architecture. D. Spongin fibres. Scale bars = A–B. 1 cm, C. 500 µm, D. 50 µm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,1676,2023]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,305,1676,1702]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Skeleton</emphasis>
: Choanosome with a delicate and irregular network of spongin fibers (
<figureCitation box="[1179,1291,1677,1703]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="30.[151,255,1532,1556]" captionTargetBox="[283,1301,412,1479]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[266,1322,397,1506]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 15: A – D. Aplysina cristagallus sp. n. Holotype (MNRJ 3528). A – B. habit after preservation. C. Skeletal architecture. D. Spongin fibres. Scale bars = A – B. 1 cm, C. 500 µm, D. 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178892/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[1238,1268,1677,1703]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" value="15.0">15</number>
C
</figureCitation>
). Bark with amber colour and 
<number box="[363,452,1717,1743]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" value="139.0" valueMax="232.0" valueMin="46.0">46–232</number>
Μm thickness (average 
<number box="[731,774,1717,1743]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" value="117.0">117</number>
Μm). Thick, black or amber pith, 
<number box="[1172,1246,1717,1743]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" value="31.5" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="13.0">13–50</number>
Μm thick (average 
<number box="[199,228,1757,1783]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" value="32.0">32</number>
Μm; 
<figureCitation box="[291,398,1757,1783]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="30.[151,255,1532,1556]" captionTargetBox="[283,1301,412,1479]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[266,1322,397,1506]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 15: A – D. Aplysina cristagallus sp. n. Holotype (MNRJ 3528). A – B. habit after preservation. C. Skeletal architecture. D. Spongin fibres. Scale bars = A – B. 1 cm, C. 500 µm, D. 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178892/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[344,374,1757,1783]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" value="15.0">15</number>
D
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,1676,2023]" box="[198,1412,1796,1823]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,351,1796,1822]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Distribution</emphasis>
: Provisionally known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[784,834,1797,1823]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">type</typeStatus>
locality off the State of Bahia (
<collectingCountry box="[1202,1278,1797,1823]" name="Brazil" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Brazil</collectingCountry>
; 
<figureCitation box="[1290,1374,1797,1823]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="31.[151,255,1788,1812]" captionTargetBox="[315,1276,512,1740]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[264,1323,477,1762]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 16: Map showing the distribution of Aplysina along the Brazilian coastline. A. Aplysina cristagallus sp. n .. B. Aplysina lactuca sp. n .. C. Aplysina lingua sp. n.. D. Aplysina muricyana sp. n .. Scale bar = 500 km." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178893/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[1344,1374,1797,1823]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
A).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,1676,2023]" box="[198,886,1836,1863]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,348,1836,1862]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Bathymetry</emphasis>
: The specimen was collected at 
<quantity box="[728,773,1837,1863]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" unit="m" value="8.0">8 m</quantity>
of depth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,1676,2023]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,333,1876,1902]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Etymology</emphasis>
: The name of the species is a noun in apposition and recognizes its similarity with the rooster´s crest (crest = 
<emphasis box="[420,487,1917,1942]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">crista</emphasis>
, and rooster = 
<emphasis box="[663,735,1917,1942]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">gallus</emphasis>
in latin).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="32" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,1676,2023]" lastBlockId="31.[151,1436,152,418]" lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="32" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,312,1956,1982]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Remarks</emphasis>
: The species which appears closest to 
<taxonomicName box="[767,938,1957,1982]" class="Demospongiae" family="Aplysinidae" genus="Aplysina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Verongida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="cristagallus" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[767,938,1957,1982]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">A. cristagallus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[945,1000,1957,1983]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is 
<taxonomicName box="[1035,1185,1957,1982]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Milleporidae" genus="Millepora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="alcicornis" status="sp.n">
<emphasis box="[1035,1185,1957,1982]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">A. alcicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1193,1243,1957,1983]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" rank="species">sp.n</taxonomicNameLabel>
.. Both possess a lamelar habit, less than 
<quantity box="[440,501,1997,2023]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" unit="cm" value="1.0">1 cm</quantity>
thick, with small apical digitiform processes. However, 
<taxonomicName box="[1188,1340,1997,2022]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Milleporidae" genus="Millepora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="alcicornis" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[1188,1340,1997,2022]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">A. alcicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1351,1406,1997,2023]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is stouter and has a harder consistency, is yellowish-brown 
<emphasis box="[813,891,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">in vivo</emphasis>
becoming dark brown when preserved, and its small digitiform processes are larger, frequently ramified and located solely on top of projections. Moreover, the oscula on 
<taxonomicName box="[311,460,232,257]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Milleporidae" genus="Millepora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="alcicornis" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[311,460,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">A. alcicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[467,523,232,258]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are situated inside depressions and are surrounded by iris-type membranes. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName box="[261,434,272,297]" class="Demospongiae" family="Aplysinidae" genus="Aplysina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Verongida" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="cristagallus" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[261,434,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">A. cristagallus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[445,501,272,298]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is rather slender and possesses a very soft consistency, is bluish gray 
<emphasis box="[1354,1435,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">in vivo</emphasis>
turning into a light shade of brown after preservation, and presents more numerous fistules which are organized in crests and bear darker apical portions. Both species are thus considered well distinguished from one another.
</paragraph>
